06352nam a22012015i 9780691190655DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911906557 a10.1515/97806911906552doi  a(DE-B1597)527290  a(OCoLC)1108619508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHN90.S65bM67 2020 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a1772231 aMorton, Jennifer M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoving Up without Losing Your Way :bThe Ethical Costs of Upward Mobility /cJennifer M. Morton. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Strivers -- t1. Recognizing the Ethical Costs of Upward Mobility -- t2. Situating Ethical Costs in Context -- t3. Navigating an Evolving Identity -- t4. Resisting Complicity -- t5. Constructing an Ethical Narrative -- tConclusion: Minimizing and Mitigating Ethical Costs -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ethical and emotional tolls paid by disadvantaged college students seeking upward mobility and what educators can do to help these students flourishUpward mobility through the path of higher education has been an article of faith for generations of working-class, low-income, and immigrant college students. While we know the road usually entails financial sacrifices and hard work, very little attention has been paid to the deep personal compromises such students have to make as they enter worlds vastly different from their own. Measuring the true cost of higher education for those from disadvantaged backgrounds, Moving Up without Losing Your Way looks at the ethical dilemmas of upward mobility-the broken ties with family and friends, the severed connections with former communities, and the loss of identity-faced by students as they strive to earn a successful place in society.Drawing on philosophy, social science, personal stories, and interviews, Jennifer Morton reframes the college experience, factoring in not just educational and career opportunities but also essential relationships with family, friends, and community. Finding that student strivers tend to give up the latter for the former, negating their sense of self, Morton seeks to reverse this course. Morton urges educators to empower students with a new narrative of upward mobility-one that honestly situates ethical costs in historical, social, and economic contexts and that allows students to make informed decisions for themselves.A powerful work with practical implications, Moving Up without Losing Your Way paves a hopeful path so that students might achieve social mobility while retaining their best selves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEducational mobilityzUnited States. 0aEthics. 0aFamilieszUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aLow-income college students. 0aOpportunity costs. 0aWorking class familiesxCosts. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aAfrican American students.  aAsian American students.  aBarack Obama.  aCity College of New York.  aEthical goods.  aJohn U. Ogbu.  aMaya Beasley.  aSection 8.  aSignithia Fordham.  aSonia Sotomayor.  aacculturation.  achildcare.  acodeswitching.  acollege costs.  acourse requirements.  acultural mismatch.  aculture of poverty.  adouble-consciousness.  aeducational underachievement.  aeldercare.  afinancial aid.  afood insecurity.  ahealthcare.  aimmigrant narrative.  amagnet school.  amarginalized communities.  aonline education.  aoppositional culture.  apoverty.  aracia